\begin_layout Standard
Tannor, Ch 02, Free-particle wavepacket
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(x)=0
\]

\end_inset

Hamiltonian:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Faktor spasial 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset

 dari solusi khusus harus memenui persamaan:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H\psi(x)=E\psi(x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solusi:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi(x)=\mathrm{e}^{\pm\imath kx}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E(k)=\frac{\hbar^{2}k^{2}}{2m}=\frac{p^{2}}{2m}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dengan definisi 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\hbar k
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
berdasarkan analogi dengan energi kinetik pada mekanika klasik:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{\mathrm{cl}}=\frac{1}{2}mv_{\mathrm{cl}}^{2}=\frac{p_{\mathrm{cl}}^{2}}{2m}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the eigenvalues for a continuous spectrum, there is a physically
 acceptable solution for every value of $k$ (and every positive value of
 $E$).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining the spatial and temporal factors we obtain the particular solution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{align}\Psi(x,t) & =\mathrm{e}^{\imath kx}\mathrm{e}^{-\imath Et/\hbar}\\
 & =\mathrm{e}^{\imath\left(kx-Et/\hbar\right)}\\
 & =\mathrm{e}^{\imath\left(kx-\frac{\hbar k^{2}}{2m}t\right)}
\end{align}
\]

\end_inset

ie, particular solution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi(x,t)=\mathrm{e}^{\imath\left(kx-\frac{\hbar k^{2}}{2m}t\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We discuss some of static features of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(x,t)$
\end_inset

 in the context of wave equations in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we fix 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and vary 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we will have the same value at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k(x_{2}-x_{1})=n\left(2\pi\right)
\]

\end_inset

Choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 gives a unique definition of wavelength:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda=x_{2}-x_{1}
\]

\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k\lambda=2\pi
\]

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k=\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 characterizes the the number of radians (which is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 times the number of cycles) per unit distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
wavenumber
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of a wavenumber is a property of the solutions of any wave
 equation; what is unique to the Schroedinger equation is that 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\hbar k=h/\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 This is the de Broglie relationship that preceded wave mechanics.
 Its physical significance is that the momentum proportional to the density
 of spatial oscillations, that is, number of oscillations per unit length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now fix 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and vary 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that any wave of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{e}^{\imath\omega t}$
\end_inset

 will have the same value at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega(t_{2}-t_{1})=n\left(2\pi\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choosing
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 defines the fundamental period: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=t_{2}-t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\tau=2\pi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 characterizes the number of radians per unit time, and is called the 
\emph on
angular frequency
\emph default
; it is a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 larger than frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, defined by: 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\dfrac{1}{\tau}=\dfrac{1}{\tau_{2}-\tau_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, the definition of an angular frequency is a property of the solutions
 of any wave equation; what is unique to the Schroedinger equation is that
 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\hbar\omega=h\nu$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This relation is due to Einstein and also preceded wave mechanics by many
 years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for free particle: 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(k)=\dfrac{\hbar k^{2}}{2m}$
\end_inset

 there is a simple functional relation between 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 This functional relationship is known as the 
\emph on
dispersion relation
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in other wave equations, the dispersion relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(k)$
\end_inset

 determines both the 
\emph on
phase velocity
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
group velocity
\emph default
 of the wave:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{align}\text{phase velocity} & =\frac{\omega}{k}\\
\text{group velocity} & =\frac{\partial\omega}{\partial k}
\end{align}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is the specific functional relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 that distinguish between the motion of quantum waves from other waves that
 occur in nature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To explore the concept of phase velocity, rewrite the particular solution
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{align}\Psi(x,t) & =\exp\left[\imath k\left(x-\frac{\hbar k}{2m}t\right)\right]\\
 & =\exp\left[\imath k\left(x-vt\right)\right]
\end{align}
\]

\end_inset

As long as the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $x-vt=0$
\end_inset

 we can change the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to obtain a constant value of the wave amplitude.
 This leads to the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $x=vt$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 increases as 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 increases, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is a wave traveling 
\emph on
to the right
\emph default
 with a velocity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\frac{\hbar k}{2m}=\frac{\omega}{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the momentum of the wavepacket, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar k$
\end_inset

, the phase velocity is 
\begin_inset Formula $p/2m$
\end_inset

, which is 
\emph on
one-half the classical expression
\emph default
 for the velocity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain the classical behavior, we need to use a wavepacket and examine
 its 
\emph on
group velocity
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general solution for free-particle wavepacket:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi(x,t)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}a(k)\exp\left[\imath\left(x-\frac{\hbar k}{2m}t\right)\right]\,\mathrm{d}k
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $a(k)$
\end_inset

 may be found from the 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 wavepacket through the use of Fourier theorem.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 the wavepacket is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi(x,0)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}a(k)\mathrm{e}^{\imath kx}\,\mathrm{d}k
\]

\end_inset

Multiplying both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(-\imath k'x)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi(x,0)\mathrm{e}^{-\imath k'x}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}a(k)\mathrm{e}^{\imath kx}\mathrm{e}^{-\imath k'x}\,\mathrm{d}k
\]

\end_inset

, integrating over 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}x\,\Psi(x,0)\mathrm{e}^{-\imath k'x}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}x\,\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}a(k)\mathrm{e}^{\imath kx}\mathrm{e}^{-\imath k'x}\,\mathrm{d}k
\]

\end_inset

, and using the property of Dirac delta function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\mathrm{e}^{-\imath k'x}\mathrm{e}^{\imath kx}\,\mathrm{d}x=2\pi\delta(k-k')
\]

\end_inset

we find that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}x\,\Psi(x,0)\mathrm{e}^{-\imath k'x} & =\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}a(k)\,\mathrm{d}k\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\mathrm{d}x\,\mathrm{e}^{\imath kx}\mathrm{e}^{-\imath k'x}\\
 & =\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}a(k)\left(2\pi\delta(k-k')\right)\,\mathrm{d}k\\
 & =2\pi a(k')
\end{align*}

\end_inset

ie, (and by changing 
\begin_inset Formula $k'\rightarrow k$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a(k)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Psi(x,0)\mathrm{e}^{-\imath kx}\mathrm{d}x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rewrite: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi(x,t)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}a(k,t)\mathrm{e}^{\imath kx}\,\mathrm{d}k
\]

\end_inset

with definition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(k,t)=a(k)\mathrm{e}^{-\imath\frac{hk^{2}}{2m}t}
\]

\end_inset

We find that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a(k,t) & =a(k)\mathrm{e}^{-\imath\frac{hk^{2}}{2m}t}\\
 & =\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Psi(x,0)\mathrm{e}^{-\imath kx}\mathrm{d}x\ \mathrm{e}^{-\imath\frac{hk^{2}}{2m}t}\\
 & =\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Psi(x,0)\mathrm{e}^{-\imath\frac{hk^{2}}{2m}t}\mathrm{e}^{-\imath kx}\mathrm{d}x
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a(k,t)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\Psi(x,t)\mathrm{e}^{-\imath kx}\mathrm{d}x
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will refer to 
\begin_inset Formula $a(k,t)$
\end_inset

as the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-representation of the wavefunction.
 
\end_layout

